Let \[f(x) =
\begin{cases}
3x + 5 &\text{if }x<-3, \\
7-4x&\text{if }x\ge -3.
\end{cases}
\]Find $f(-10)$.
inference:
When $x=-10$ we are in the first branch of the piecewise definition, so:

$$f(-10)=3(-10)+5=-30+5=\boxed{-25}.$$

**Final Answer: $$\boxed{-25}$$. I hope it is correct.**
ground_truth: Because $-10<-3$, we use the first case to determine that $f(-10) = 3(-10) + 5 = \boxed{-25}$.
